Decisions

Purpose:
- Public-safe current decision memory for active product, architecture, documentation, and claim-boundary choices.

Verification status: active operational memory; verify against code, docs, and reports before relying on it.
Memory scope: governing decisions that should steer future agents until explicitly changed.
Public-safe status: safe for source control; contains no credential values.
Update route: update this local file when governing decisions change; submit durable public-safe decision summaries to https://memoryendpoints.com/api/matm/memory-events/submit when authenticated.
Source of truth: current repository state, `.uai/totem.uai`, `AGENTS.md`, `docs/reports/final-readiness-report.md`, and user instructions.
Next action for agents: preserve these decisions unless current code, reports, or direct human instruction supersedes them.
Must not expose: raw API keys, bearer tokens, FTP credentials, database passwords, private keys, private handoff payloads, raw one-time keys, or private deployment values.

Current governing decisions:
- Keep `E:\MemoryEndpoints.com` as the single source of truth for MemoryEndpoints.com and MultiAgentMemory.com content.
- Keep local `.uai` active always. Hosted MATM augments `.uai`; it does not replace it.
- Keep active `.uai` date-free active operational memory only.
- Do not add `.uai` files named `short-term-memory.uai`, `active-memory.uai`, `current-state.uai`, `project-state.uai`, `working-state.uai`, or equivalent under any purpose or interpretation.
- Store deep detail in docs, reports, MATM records, or other durable targets, then point to those from typed `.uai` files.
- Store company, workspace, and project knowledge trees as protected database records, not as generated filesystem trees. Filesystem reports can be temporary evidence or source input, but crawlable/searchable company knowledge belongs in the database source of truth.
- Treat `docs/` as transitional migration/evidence material only. After the knowledge is moved deliberately into MemoryEndpoints.com, `docs/` should not remain as a parallel source-of-truth documentation tree.
- Do not bulk-import report archives into company knowledge. Ingest reports deliberately through reviewed, source-notated database document writes so scope, category, project placement, and context are correct.
- Process one source report at a time, but do not force a multi-topic report into one oversized page. Preserve the canonical source, then create semantically bounded pages with explicit source provenance so retrieval remains focused without losing evidence.
- Treat taxonomy paths as first-class wiki navigation. Each knowledge document needs title, description, keywords, and one or more hierarchy paths; multiple hierarchy placement is expected when a concept belongs in more than one context.
- Treat every retained external URL as its own canonical data type with URL, host, site name, page title, description, keywords, review state, and crawl state. Connect it to knowledge pages through contextual citation records; do not rely on raw URLs embedded only in report text.
- External-link upsert is metadata indexing, not permission to crawl. Reject non-public hosts and credential-bearing URLs, and require a separate reviewed crawl decision before fetching remote content.
- Do not copy public NeuralWikis wiki content, branding, or generated public site material.
- Do not claim certification, endorsement, hidden credential validation, automatic repository writes, or live production database support that is not actually verified.
- Use MemoryEndpoints.com home page for inbound MemoryEndpoints links; UAIX wizard fragments are setup-option references for UAIX.
- Keep README files as human repository or site documentation only. Do not use README files as active `.uai` memory, handoff-bucket guidance, or intake completion evidence.
